The problem is that by immediately calling printWindow.close() after printWindow.print(), you are closing the window before the print dialog has a chance to process the document. To fix it, you need to wait until the printing is finished or the print dialog has been opened before closing the window.

Here are a few approaches you can use:

1. Use a Timeout:
You can delay the closing of the window with setTimeout so that it isnâ€™t closed immediately. For example:

â€ƒâ€ƒprintWindow.document.open();
â€ƒâ€ƒprintWindow.document.write("toto");
â€ƒâ€ƒprintWindow.document.close();
â€ƒâ€ƒprintWindow.focus();
â€ƒâ€ƒprintWindow.print();
â€ƒâ€ƒsetTimeout(function () {
â€ƒâ€ƒâ€ƒâ€ƒprintWindow.close();
â€ƒâ€ƒ}, 1000); // Adjust the timing as needed

2. Use the onafterprint Event:
Modern browsers support the onafterprint event, which triggers after the print dialog has been closed. For example:

â€ƒâ€ƒprintWindow.document.open();
â€ƒâ€ƒprintWindow.document.write("toto");
â€ƒâ€ƒprintWindow.document.close();
â€ƒâ€ƒprintWindow.focus();
â€ƒâ€ƒprintWindow.print();
â€ƒâ€ƒprintWindow.onafterprint = function() {
â€ƒâ€ƒâ€ƒâ€ƒprintWindow.close();
â€ƒâ€ƒ};

Both methods ensure that the window remains open long enough for the print process to initiate properly.

Note:
â€¢ Make sure you remove the 'text/plain' parameter from document.open() (unless you have a specific reason to keep it) because by default you might want to treat it as HTML if you're writing HTML content.
â€¢ The exact method might vary depending on the browser and its settings.

Using one of these approaches should fix the issue so that the document is correctly proposed for printing before the window is closed.

